Multiple sclerosis is a genetic disease of the nervous system, which affects thousands in every country. It has been called one type "cancer". As well as numerous symptoms (such
- - depression, anxiety), it can be deadly if left untreated and causes long term disability or even death for those with weakened immune systems. People have many different forms of MS but most are characterized by severe muscle weakness caused chiefly through degenerative conditions such anemia, impaired vision due to arthritis [1], atrophy of tissue around nerve cells and damage involving damaged axons between nerves. However there may also occur other types that affect skin conductivity via electrical conduction failure at synapses; often they will cause numbness along extremities whereas others require prosthetic limbs requiring extensive joint replacement surgery. Most patients do not know whether their condition represents another form than just chronic wasting syndrome although some doctors believe so because certain characteristics suggest otherwise.[2][3]. The first manifestation was seen very early on when people were found walking across busy streets without shoes/leggings[4], having difficulty maintaining balance during strenuous exercise,[5],[6]- these include leg paralysis where feet float under heavy objects like chairs despite footwear being used... In 2002 research showed that half of all adults had experienced 'walking into thin air' while taking part within 7 years previous....

Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a disease of the nervous system that causes weakness, paralysis and ultimately death. There are two types; primary or secondary. Primary MS affects one side only while secondary forms affect both sides. The condition occurs when inflammation in nerve cells triggers uncontrolled cell growth which leads to damage to surrounding tissues such as bone marrow.
            When people with this disorder become old they lose their ability for movement but gain it back by using new muscles formed during therapy called motor skills training. These exercises help repair damaged nerves so you can move normally again after many months away from work. Most patients experience no difficulty walking up stairs without assistance, though some may need support just like any other sufferer out there! Once healed your legs will be able do almost anything around town! That's why these activities require daily practice even if you don't have regular exercise classes at home!!
